# <span id="16">16</span>

>     taisi [de`] psu^xros me'n e?'gento ðu^mos
>     pa`r d? i?'eisi ta` pte'ra ...

But the spirit within them turned chill and down dropped their wings.

The Scholist quotes this to show that Sappho says the same thing of
doves as Pindar (Pyth. 1-10) says of the eagle of Zeus.

Another reading is psau^kros, "light", for psu^xros, "moist or chill."
The sense would then be "the spirit within them became light and they
relaxed their wings in rest."

